To create a function that finds prime numbers within a given range using the Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm in JavaScript, you can use the following code:

```javascript
function findPrimes(start, end, range) {
  if (typeof start !== 'number' || typeof end !== 'number' || typeof range !== 'number') {
    throw new Error('All parameters must be numbers');
  }

  if (start < 0 || end < 0 || range < 0) {
    throw new Error('All parameters must be positive numbers');
  }

  const primes = [];
  const isPrime = new Array(range + 1).fill(true);
  isPrime[0] = false;
  isPrime[1] = false;

  for (let i = 2; i * i <= range; i++) {
    if (isPrime[i]) {
      for (let j = i * i; j <= range; j += i) {
        isPrime[j] = false;
      }
    }
  }

  for (let i = start; i <= end; i++) {
    if (isPrime[i]) {
      primes.push(i);
    }
  }

  return primes;
}
```

This function first checks if the provided parameters are numbers and positive. It then initializes an array `isPrime` of size `range + 1` with all values set to `true`. It sets the values at indices 0 and 1 to `false` since they are not prime numbers.

The function then applies the Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm to mark all the composite (non-prime) numbers by iterating from 2 up to the square root of the range. For each prime number found, it marks all its multiples as composite.

Finally, the function iterates from the start to the end number and adds the prime numbers to the `primes` array. This array is then returned as the result.

