Here is a Java program that checks whether an integer is prime or composite, validates the input range, ensures the input is positive, and keeps track of the counts of prime and composite integers entered by the user:

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class PrimeCompositeChecker {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        int primeCount = 0;
        int compositeCount = 0;

        System.out.println("Enter an integer within the range -10^6 to 10^6 (inclusive):");

        while (true) {
            int num = scanner.nextInt();

            if (num < -Math.pow(10, 6) || num > Math.pow(10, 6)) {
                System.out.println("Invalid input! Please enter an integer within the range -10^6 to 10^6 (inclusive):");
                continue;
            }

            if (num <= 0) {
                System.out.println("Invalid input! Please enter a positive integer:");
                continue;
            }

            boolean isPrime = true;
            for (int i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
                if (num % i == 0) {
                    isPrime = false;
                    break;
                }
            }

            if (isPrime) {
                System.out.println(num + " is a prime number.");
                primeCount++;
            } else {
                System.out.println(num + " is a composite number.");
                compositeCount++;
            }

            System.out.println("Enter another integer within the range -10^6 to 10^6 (inclusive):");
        }

        System.out.println("Total prime numbers entered: " + primeCount);
        System.out.println("Total composite numbers entered: " + compositeCount);
    }
}
```

In this program, we use a `while` loop to continuously prompt the user to enter an integer. If the input is outside the valid range or is not positive, the program displays an error message and asks the user to enter a valid integer.

To check whether the input is prime or composite, we use a loop that checks if the number is divisible by any number from 2 to the square root of the number. If it is divisible by any number, it is a composite number; otherwise, it is a prime number.

The program keeps track of the counts of prime and composite numbers entered using two variables `primeCount` and `compositeCount`. At the end, it displays the counts.

