Preemptive multitasking refers to a scheduling technique where the operating system can interrupt a running task to allocate the processor to another task. Non-preemptive multitasking, on the other hand, allows a task to run until it voluntarily yields control to the operating system.

Examples of operating systems that use preemptive multitasking include Windows, Linux, and macOS. These operating systems use techniques such as time slicing or priority-based scheduling to determine when to interrupt a running task and switch to another. Programming languages like C, C++, and Java can be used to develop applications for these operating systems.

In preemptive multitasking, the operating system typically uses a scheduler to determine the order in which tasks are executed. The scheduler may use different algorithms to prioritize tasks based on factors like their priority level, time requirements, or I/O needs. The scheduler allocates processor time to tasks based on these factors.

Here is a code snippet demonstrating task scheduling in preemptive multitasking using C++:

```cpp
// Define a Task struct to represent a task
struct Task {
  int id;
  int priority;
};

// Define a function to compare tasks based on their priority
bool compareTasks(const Task& task1, const Task& task2) {
  return task1.priority > task2.priority;
}

// Create a priority queue of tasks
std::priority_queue<Task, std::vector<Task>, decltype(&compareTasks)> taskQueue(&compareTasks);

// Add tasks to the queue
taskQueue.push({1, 5});
taskQueue.push({2, 3});
taskQueue.push({3, 7});

// Execute tasks in priority order
while (!taskQueue.empty()) {
  Task currentTask = taskQueue.top();
  taskQueue.pop();

  // Execute the task
  executeTask(currentTask);
}
```

Potential issues with this code snippet include the lack of handling of concurrent access to the task queue. To address this, synchronization mechanisms like mutexes or semaphores can be used.

To modify the task scheduling algorithm to accommodate priority-based scheduling, the code snippet can be revised by introducing a priority value to the Task struct and changing the comparison function to compare based on the priority value.

