Here's an example of how you can create an array with 1000 random numbers between -1000 and 1000, sort it in descending order using the bubble sort algorithm, and implement a validation check to ensure that no duplicate numbers are present:

```java
import java.util.Random;

public class RandomArraySorting {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] array = generateRandomArray(1000, -1000, 1000);
        System.out.println("Original Array:");
        printArray(array);

        // Sort the array in descending order
        bubbleSortDescending(array);
        System.out.println("\nSorted Array (Descending Order):");
        printArray(array);

        // Check for duplicate numbers
        if (hasDuplicates(array)) {
            System.out.println("\nThe array contains duplicate numbers.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("\nThe array does not contain any duplicate numbers.");
        }
    }

    public static int[] generateRandomArray(int size, int min, int max) {
        int[] array = new int[size];
        Random random = new Random();
        for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
            array[i] = random.nextInt((max - min) + 1) + min;
        }
        return array;
    }

    public static void bubbleSortDescending(int[] array) {
        int n = array.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
                if (array[j] < array[j + 1]) {
                    // Swap array[j] and array[j+1]
                    int temp = array[j];
                    array[j] = array[j + 1];
                    array[j + 1] = temp;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    public static boolean hasDuplicates(int[] array) {
        int n = array.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                if (array[i] == array[j]) {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }

    public static void printArray(int[] array) {
        for (int num : array) {
            System.out.print(num + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }
}
```

This code snippet first generates a random array of 1000 numbers between -1000 and 1000 using the `generateRandomArray()` method. It then prints the original array, sorts it in descending order using the bubble sort algorithm implemented in the `bubbleSortDescending()` method, and prints the sorted array.

Finally, it checks for duplicate numbers in the array using the `hasDuplicates()` method and prints whether the array contains duplicate numbers or not. The `printArray()` method is used to print the array elements.

